segments.text: Second, let's see if we've got anything on that.
We're here today to try to get what I have in background information in my 18 years with the association.
Yeah, I'm going to go ahead and turn it on.
We're trying what I really would like to talk to you about.
Well, anyway, that was the way the book is going to develop.
with the county agent, animal husbandry problem, and probably deal a lot with, I noticed in the literature over there, the quacks or whatever they want to call them.
Been through all the files.
thing.
So that brings us up to about World War II.
And then I think the next chapter is going to deal probably just with the concept of urbanization, modern contemporary developments, and so forth, changing profile of the profession.
Somewhere along there, and I don't know quite what chapter it's going to fall into, will be new technology and techniques and problems within the profession, women coming in.
All of this is going to go somewhere.
And then you probably got your TVMA newsletter and there's an insert going out in that thing to all the vets asking them to send in any

information or experiences or something and so we're going to try to run about two chapters which will really be a personality profile I think it'd be fun you know because everybody has a good story sure so what and what I'd like to talk to you about you tell me too because I'm getting my feet wet but one thing I want to know is simply your personal background and how you got in associated with the Texas Veterinary Medical Association
Then maybe some sort of broad comment about what you think is historically important in doing a study like this or a book.
What do you think people need to know?
And then maybe get into, you might say, some specific information regarding your tenure as director.
One theme I want to try to pursue throughout all this thing
I don't know quite how we're going to define it yet, but the human-animal bond.
This has always been with us as part of life.
And here is how we handled it in early Texas and modern Texas and so forth.
And it's still very much with us.
So there's going to be a caring theme, I hope, that will come out of all this.
That's very, very good.
So tell me where you got started.
Well, I got started, of course, I have an agricultural background as far as education.
From A&M?
From Texas A&M.
I'm a 1954 graduate of Texas A&M, and I got a degree in agricultural education, as a matter of fact.
And, of course, I had an agricultural background being reared on a farm and kind of a diversified farm and ranch.
My daddy had eight children, so he did everything in agriculture from trade cattle to farm peanuts, cotton,
grew hogs and horses and so forth.
Where were you?
Houston County, Texas, which is a little town called Grape Land, Texas.
Where I went to high school, I grew up about four and a half miles out of the country.
South of Jasper?
Where is Grape Land?
Grape Land is in Houston County, north of Crockett.
South of Palestine.
It's just across the Trinity River.
You know, East Texas begins and ends at the Trinity River.
At least in that part of the state.
And I grew up on a small, diversified farm.
I grew up on a small farm, several hundred acre farm, but we did all the small things in agriculture.
We weren't big operators.
And the county agent was an important man.
Oh, absolutely.
And so was the ag teacher.
Probably in my community, the ag culture teacher was the most prominent person in agriculture.
He did some of this old
They looked to the ag teacher to be the authority that knew more than the producer did.
Of course, the county agent was too, but in fact, my greatest influence to do what I did was to call in my vocational agriculture teacher.
His name was J.C. Schultz, and he was an old pioneer.
And he encouraged me because he wanted me to be a teacher like he was.
into vocational agriculture and future farmer work and I became a public speaker for the chapter.
In fact, I won second in the state public speaking contest in 1947.
That's a long way back.
I was only about 14, 15 years old.
But then, of course, I was never anything that I was going to do except be a vocational agriculture teacher because that's
That was my motivation, and I went to Texas A&M and graduated in 1954 with a degree in ag education.
At that time, the Korean War was on, and all the older guys that had already graduated two or three years ago were coming back from the war.
So it made it pretty hard for a young man 22 years old to get a job in teaching.
So Extension was doing some expansion in those days.
So I went into Extension, and I was in county agricultural work.
in Anderson County in Palestine as an assistant, and then I was an associate agent in Panola County, which was working with adult farm and ranch people.
At that time... My dad was an old county agent.
Oh, really?
Yeah, he was in Plaquemine Parish, Louisiana in the 1920s and early 30s.
Another world.
He had a lot of stories, didn't he?
Yes, he did.
But anyway, I got involved in farm organization work.
The Texas Farm Bureau was beginning to expand into East Texas.
They had never really had any members in East Texas.
And they were beginning to expand their membership over there, and it was a very slow proposition.

I got very interested in farm organization work, and about that time they offered me an opportunity to become a field representative for the Texas Farm Bureau, which would be organizing and working with county farm bureaus.
And the only locations they had were one in Austin and one in Lubbock.
I didn't have much trouble with that, so I came to Austin.
Eventually, I moved to Taylor and then came to Austin.
And as it would work out, they asked me if I'd work in the legislative office during the session to help out the legislative director because they needed somebody to come in and help.
So I got very, very interested in government repairs and legislative work.
And back to the point, I was just fascinated with it.
So, anyway, I told them that I wanted to go back.
I didn't know how I was doing that work, but I wanted to go back to the field and if it worked out fine.
If it didn't, I still, but I enjoy it and I like it.
So, as luck would have it, the person that I worked with at the legislative office at Farm Bureau decided to take another job in the Valley, running another organization.
And at that time, I pretty much settled out that I was going to stay where I was.
But then, to make a long story short, they influenced me to come back.
to take the legislative office over.
I was 29 years old.
That's a nice job.
And I was a little scared to death, but I think that's what made me succeed, because I knew that I had a pretty big responsibility.
And I stayed with them for two sessions, a 63 and 65 session, 1963 and 1965.
And that's when my acquaintance struck up with the Veterinary Medical Association.
That time, 1962, was the first year that Texas passed a sales tax.
It was a 2% limited sales tax.
Well, there was a big push on to exempt certain items, including food and drugs.
Well, it turned out that veterinary drugs did not meet the definition of drugs that they were going to exempt.
The executive director at that time was Glenn Savage, who you'll run across somewhere in the history of this organization.
And he was down here from Fort Worth where the office was at that time.

And I was with the Farm Bureau, and he asked me if I would help him try to secure an exemption for veterinary drugs, because the definition of drugs was for, was human drugs, for a practitioner of the healing arts.
The definition didn't fit the veterinarian.
The veterinarian at that time, and I don't know where they are yet, was not described as a practitioner of the healing arts, so that's the way the exemption read in the tax bill in 1962.
So they asked me, and at that time it was a big fight to not take any amendments on the floor.
Everybody agreed that we were going to have a tax bill, but they took one amendment and were afraid to destroy the bill.
So they asked me, and I said, well, I think the only chance we've got
is to go to the comptroller's office and see if he would make an interpretation, if he on his own would make an interpretation that veterinary drug did indeed fit the exemption.
So we got a comptroller's ruling on that for that session.
And that was the beginning of my, even my knowledge of the association.
And that was their big, that was their big bag in 1962.
So you did get that interpretation from the Comptroller?
We did get it.
And then that stuck basically there?
Yeah, what we did later, of course, was write it.
We did get a rewrite of the bill, but at that time, as I said, we could have... Nobody was really...
I think we could have gotten it, but the deal was made that we weren't going to change the tax bill.
So that means we left out.
When you left out, you're always left out.
Chances are.
So anyway...
We got that done, and then, of course, they were very nice to me and appreciated it.
And, of course, it was in my interest, too, but I represented people who had cattle, you know, and kind of worked together.
So anyhow, about in the 1965 session, we came back and rewrote the tax bill to make it clear.
other than just the comptroller's ruling that the veterinary drug indeed was exempt, along with other prescription drugs.
It had to be a prescription drug.

And so, anyway, about old July of 1965, Glenn Savage, the executive secretary at that time they called him, called me up and wanted to know if I wanted to be considered for the executive secretary of the Texas Veterinary Medicine Association.
I told them I did not because I had a job and I wasn't looking for one.
And they said, well, would you just agree to interview with the committee?
And they had put this thing in the Wall Street Journal.
You can't believe how many hundreds of applications they had even then.
But they weeded it down to about, I don't know, 20 or so, and I agreed to come.
And like a lot of things happen, I did agree to...

to accept their offer which really was a substantial raise for me at that time and I had to make a decision and I did and I never regretted it because I made a lot of friends and I was really didn't know it at the time but I was taking on a developing organization I was taking on a developing organization that
really was fixing to get into its own.
In other words, it had come to the point in 1965, they were at the place where the growth could really occur.
In other words, if certain things were plugged in, and fortunately we were able to do that, that the growth was going to be there.
We called it a very progressive era that we were in.

veterinarians were beginning to be more accepted, the sophistication of small animal practice, the growth of cities, and the fact that the veterinarian in the country was taking on a different and better image.
And we were getting more quality trained, smart people out in the field.
We were getting somebody that was above the average agricultural type person that might wind up in ag ed or
or animal husbandry.
We were getting a real the real sharp kids coming in.
So I had just a good time.
And I had had enough experience, I guess that organization that I knew some things that had to be done.
In other words, you had to start doing some new things, some things that were not being done just when I came Henry
We pretty much concentrated, it was a one-man office, one secretary office.
It was in Fort Worth.
I went up and personally moved it down myself with the help of a trucker.
And that was one of the considerations that I made, that I would not be interested in the job if I hadn't moved to Fort Worth.
Okay, that's what I'm wondering.
So that was part of the deal.
That was part of the deal that I struck, and I really cut across a lot of...
a lot of emotions when we did this because the office had always been there.
The treasurer had been treasurer for, Dr.
Cloud had been treasurer for many, many years, very much respected, and that meant that he would no longer be treasurer.
Who was that?
Dr.
Cloud.
I believe it was E.G.
Cloud.
I saw that literature.
He was a very, very great man.
I think he was a graduate of the old Kansas City Veterinary College.
And at that time, he was in his 70s, and
Of course, he seemed like a very, very old person to me.
Of course, it doesn't seem like he's quite that old anymore at that age.
But a very nice person.
But I was the person that, and with Dr. Wallace Cardwell was president then.
Dr. Cardwell said, I'll take care of it.
I'll talk to Dr.
Cloud.
And I'll talk to the Fort Worth veterinarians.
And I will clear the air for you.
And the board has agreed to go along with what I recommend.
And that won't be your problem.
And I said, Bill.
That's the deal.
So anyway, to tell you the story and short it down, I went up and visited Dr.
Plow.
We went over to the bank, got all the records.
If you need to stop and do something else, go ahead.
No, no, no.
I've got the next phone call.
I've got a bill I'm trying to get introduced today.
It's the last day to introduce it, so it's been hanging in the senator's office over there.
That's an orange.
Yeah, it's going.
Go ahead.
Where would you like for me to pick that up?
Go ahead.
You're moving from Fort Worth to Austin.
Right.
And where did you locate in Austin?
Well, that's an interesting story.
I guess that's not important.
That's an interesting story.
I'd always office downtown because at that time I was still a fairly young person.
I was 33 years old at that time.
And I was assuming that they'd say, well, let's move back to downtown.
But I think they felt that the change of me moving to the suburbs, which...
could hardly be called a suburb now without Hancock's Shopping Center, which is out on Interstate 35 north.
You'll see a Sears store out there.
But anyway, they had a small office building out there.
So we negotiated for a very small space, three little offices in it, reception room, kind of a work area, storage area, and then my office in that.
And I think they thought it would be good for me to get away from my...
the influence of agriculture and the people that were around there thought maybe change would be good to get me thinking maybe more veterinary matters away from the old.
And I accepted that, and that certainly wasn't a consideration in me coming to work.
We stayed out there for two years and tried to renegotiate a contract.
And it turned out that Sears owned that building, Homework Corporation.
And they gave us some very, very stringent terms that we couldn't afford.
We were still struggling.
When we started, we had a $25,000 budget.
I've got some notes on that.
I think it was, I know it was less than $30,000, but something like a $25,000 annual budget.
We had only about between 600 and 700 members.
So at that time, we were only getting, I believe, $25 or
head for members so you can figure out the budget pretty quick.
Anyway, we decided then to move back downtown.

We moved down on Browder Street and stayed there for three or four years and that building was leased to the state and we moved over to 6th and Congress, which is called the Scarborough Building, and we began to try to expand the size of our offices and add to our staff at that time.
because we were adding programs all this time.
We were adding new things.

When I first came, it was the convention, it was membership, it was editing the Texas Veterinary Medical Journal, and it was a summer seminar, and maybe one or two specialized seminars at other times during the year.
But it really was the base of the activity.
Say that again.
So TVMA convention, summer seminars, the journal, the TVMA journal.
Right, convention, membership, of course, retention and development.
Journal editing, which was a six-time-a-year publication that came out every month, which still does, I guess.
And...

ready to continue education program convention at the convention both continuing education and the business meeting type of situation and then we would have a summer seminar which was our semi-annual meeting more or less where the boards got together and then we would put on a maybe special seminar too for say the dairy practitioner or the small animal practitioner this was before the local associations developed strongly before they could put on their own seminars
They were beginning to develop what I call the local association like Harris County.
Was that going on before you came in?
There were some local associations then.
Had that been basically sponsored by the Texas?
No, it was more... Or was that just a local spontaneous type...
Right, we were supportive of it and the association had been supportive.
But it was pretty much a social event for the local people to stay together and to talk.
more talk about problems, and then later on they got on into continuing education.
I want to come back to that a little bit and talk about the relations between the local association and the state.
Excuse me, go ahead.
So when I came, as I say, we were beginning to expand.
At that time, I had seen the fact that we had to get... One reason they hired me, of course, is that they knew I knew something about the legislative process.

and they knew that they would never ever be completely free of the legislative process because of the practice act and because of other things like tax taxes and things that affect veterinarians in the legislative process and of course I've had enough of an association background to I guess to get a little credibility on that side so
But I began to see... Had Savage or any of your predecessors actively really been involved with the legislature?
They always hired somebody.
They hired a lobbyist, kind of like I am now, to come in and handle certain bills and certain defensive measures.
Savage didn't know anything about legislation and didn't want to.
That was not his bag, and that was acceptable.
But he knew that it had to be done, so he hired...
people on the spot.
Okay, so your retention was with full knowledge that this is what we need to do.
We need to focus in this direction.
Right.
It was a very strong point.
And, of course, I knew that, and I still believe this, that all associations, you've got to have an association manager first, and you've got to have a lobbyist second.
I mean, that may sound like I'm talking against my profession, but
The management association legislation is just one part of it.
It's very, very important.
And it's real good that you get somebody that's what we call a double-deed that can do association management and legislation.
And of course, I had a keen interest in the legislation, and I wanted to do it.
But it's very, very time-consuming to be both.
It takes away from time.
So you have to have a very good number two person in the office sometimes to try to do both.
I always did.
I never spent a dollar on a lobbyist for an association.
I never spent any money on an attorney.
I did the whole thing.
But we hired a CPA to be our auditor of our books like always.
Did you hire an assistant director or anything?
I hired a real good number one girl Friday night.
It took me two or three people to find that girl.
But she was from a military family and needed a job and was very intelligent and had a lot of experience in typing.
And I later made her office manager and started personnel.
Who was that man?
Her name was Virginia Houghton, H-O-U-G-H-T-O-N. Everybody called her Jenny.
She was an Iowa girl, an Iowa boy in the Air Force.
Found out at Berkshire, here in Austin.
And...
She's very, very loyal, very supportive to me over those years and pretty much ran the office.
And I can say for years, Henry, there was not anybody but Jenny.
We did it all.
And I can say we're beginning to see the need to expand into new areas.
For instance, I set up a political action committee called VPAT, Veterans Political Action Committee.
I set that up to try to get the veterinarians involved in the financial end of legislation.
You know, the story is that you can't play the legislative game unless you play in the political game.
Yeah.
So I was trying to promote that and did, and we began to raise a little money to help certain people that had helped us, you know, pass bills and kill things.
Yeah.
I can't remember the year, but you'll find it in the history of the organization.
We set it up prior to 1970, somewhere between 1965 and 1970, we set up the Veterinary Political Action Committee.
The idea being that you would make an extra dollar contribution.
We never did say it had to be $50.
We never did refuse to accept any amount.
But it was kind of a volunteer assessment, not an assessment, but a request on the membership.
It didn't come out on the membership.
It was just an appeal that we made every so often to give to the... As you would any political action committee any time.
And it had to be personal contributions.
Right, yeah.
That made it a little tougher, but...
We had an influence of enough people to get it started.
Most of them are board members, past presidents, officers, or those that were real active in the local association.
Is that still going?
They still have it running.
I think they've been able to raise pretty good money lately.
Their practice act was up last session before the sunset, and they needed some friends, and they needed radical action to
So we set that up.
Really, I did that for two reasons.
One was to try to... Did you work for them on that incident?
All around it.
All around it?
You mean the BPAC?
Yeah, no, I mean now.
I mean the last session of the legislature.
I worked around and with them.
That's kind of another story.
Okay, I want to ask you that.
The agricultural groups were...
or a little bit concerned about some of the things, then they were putting me in a very tough position.
Anyway, I was able to do some things.
But anyway, we set that up, and it became apparent that still we needed some other things.
At that time, the late 60s, there was a big push on to require mandatory continuing education for professionals.
And we were scared to death.
As a matter of fact, we didn't know how to get a handle on it.
But there was a lot of pressure coming down from the federal people to require mandatory continuing education.
So we set up the Texas Academy of Veterinary Practice, Texas Academy of Veterinary Practice.
OK, my next question.
Yeah, it sounded like it.
TABP, Texas Academy of Veterinary Practice, which Billy Tremere from San Antonio was the first president.
And Billy asked me when he came in, he said,
I want to do something.
I was sending him a blank.
The Texas Academy of Veterinary Practice.
Texas Academy of Veterinary Practice.
He said, what is the most needed thing we need to do?
We've been in legislation.
We've broadened our continuing education program.
What do we need to do?
This thing scares me about mandatory CE.
What can we do?
I said, I think what the professionals need to do, the veterinarians, is to establish some image
that we're already doing a lot voluntarily.
And I said, you know, the physicians have what they call an academy of physicians.
These are the people that go a step beyond.
And I said, I'm not talking about, you know, getting into the issuing of some certificate for some school that you're going to a lot of advanced things.
We're talking about practical things that practitioners do.
And he said, well, let's look into that.

So we talked to some people, including the Texas Medical Association and the Texas Academy of Medicine and some of those, and he said, why don't we look at the possibility of setting up an academy where we've set some standards where you have to have so many hours of continuing education before you can belong to the academy, and you have to keep so many hours up so you can maintain your membership, and that way we can demonstrate not only to the regulators but to the public.

that we already you know we didn't we didn't leave school and forget learning you know we we left the school and we're continuing so we set that up in 1970 that was five years after i got there i guess that was the second outside second other group that we blended in and we're very careful that all of these are all all these things are under the umbrella of tbma they were never
Yeah, because you would create a monster there, couldn't you?
Oh, yeah.
And it still is that way.
You can't be an academy if you're not a TVA.
You have to be the way the bylaws were drawn, and I'm sure they're going to change a little bit.
So we set that up, and then we began to get more deeply involved in stepping up our activity and continuing education.
At that time, insurance was another thing that began to surface as being a need.
And everybody in the association business that was in the insurance business made money, unlike today.
You know, there's just plenty of people that don't want to be in the insurance business and shouldn't be.
And I got into the association.
I would warn them to be careful about getting into the insurance.
But we got into the insurance business, set up our own hospital program, our own life insurance thing, you know, through companies.
We sponsored them, by the way.
So it's a group insurance for all purposes, medical, for liability, disability.
Workers' comp, set up the whole gauntlet of a general insurance coverage.
That's when we really hired our third person, our next member of the staff, named Claire Trautman, T-R-O-U-T-M-A, Claire again.
for some reason had a military background, too.
Her husband was in the military and they retired here.
Spell that again, Clara.
Clara, C-L-A-R-E-T-R-O-U-T-M-A-N, Troutman.
And we hired her to administer the insurance program in cooperation with our sponsor, the insurance organization of the company that we represented for us.
And in addition, that gave us another staff member to help on other things.
She wasn't hired exclusively for the purpose, but it gave us another person to work in convention work, another hand, another person to put out work.
But that lasted, it went down with the story of the insurance,
business in general, it just got horrible.
We did another thing too to raise money.
We were looking for supplemental income.
We were trying to keep them raising dues.
Okay, so you were taking kind of a fee on the policies.
We were taking a commission out of the company, the sponsoring agency that we worked with was giving us a percentage of the premium that was paid in.
Did you sell your policy to different carriers or...
Right.
What we did, we got an agency out of Fort Worth to set it up.
And he was in complete control of finding the source.
The only heat we put on him was that it had to be competitive.
AVMA also had an insurance program.
And some of our members are already in AVMA.
But I have to be honest, we did it...
Two reasons.
One is to get some extra income.
Two was to get some extra staff.
I mean, I'm talking like a manager now.
Yeah, sure.
I don't know whether the board saw it that way completely, but at least they supported it.
Well, it should have been a benefit to the members, too.
It was a member service, and that's another thing we were getting to stress was member services.
You know, we stressed CE, we stressed political action, we stressed the academy through CE, CE through the academy.
And we began to get more involved in member services.
At that point, we began to put in a few products that large animal practices could use, like vials and needles for brucellosis testing.
We were the source of that.
You know, they could only get the federal program testing for brucellosis.
And I don't know how many years I was a disease brucellosis because it was contagious abortion.
And federal people had a program that went through the state animal health commission
practitioner was authorized to do all the health testing and blood testing.
But they would not release the materials to just anybody.
They wanted them to go through an agency type situation, either through the government or through us.
So we convinced them to go through the association.
And that gave us another small source of income.
And let me ask you this.
think about or try to develop this into a broader cooperative type of supply?
No, we didn't.
We thought about it some.
Because that's a danger.
Yeah, we ran into too many potential conflicts.
You know, the veterinarian likes to and should do business in his community.
So we didn't go into the cooperative.
We didn't go into trying to sell him all of his needs for his hospital.
So this is a specialty product that's really controlled basically through that.
The only one that we were really into.
We did have some pamphlets that we made available.
They'd been into that before I came, some pamphlets on client pamphlets.
We were into that somewhat.
But that gave us some more incomes, another source.
And by that time, we were beginning to need some more staff.
We began to hire more clerical-type staff, people that could get in.
turnout work.
We had three people, myself, Jenny, and Claire, that were pretty much the upper level staff.
Then we began to hire support people, in which when I left, before I left, there'd be nine, we had nine people there, including we hired a publications person, that person to do our printing, to
lay out our publications.
See, I did all that myself.
I laid out the publication.
I wrote the publication.
I laid it down.
I did everything except printing.
And then we hired a young man to come in to run our printing.
At that time, we were real deep in those new entities.
We were producing a lot of material.
As you might imagine, Academy had a lot of material.
BPAC had a lot of material.

insurance program and all that so we were getting kind of getting bogged down into a workload then about that time we uh got interested in developing a foundation i don't know whether this follows in the sequence here go right on because these are key uh areas of development that's that's fine i'll straighten them out so we decided that uh what can we do that would
augment all the things that we're already doing.
So we came up with the idea of a non-profit C3 foundation.
It wanted to be tax exempt and it could raise money.
It could also go to other groups who had money and dedicate money to things like continuing education, research.
We had a long-range plan of a foundation
building a building, you know, a museum and some of these other things you probably heard talked about.
They were way back.
But we were trying to establish another organization that could be supported not only by veterinarians but by others.
People in the drug business, people who had other foundations who wanted to support.
It also gave us a non-profit status that we really didn't need.
In other words, we could legally run all of our
A lot of our printing, a lot of our CE could go through the foundation if we wanted to.
And it would give us a break on things.
See, the C6 Corporation was what the association is.
And it had certain things that were a little different from the foundation, although we were also
A tax exempt, there were some things that we could not do like we could do on the foundation.
We did the foundation primarily to do some things the association couldn't do.
And it floundered for a while.
All foundations do, and I've been involved in some.
We've been in them.
They're slow to develop.
People come pretty impatient with them.
But you can't do that.
that has to be allowed to grow.
And I guess we did the foundation probably in the middle of the late 70s when we got into developing the foundation.
Now, who took leadership in that among the membership?
Were there people who really got into that?
Yeah, what we did on that is we set it up to where we'd have some past presidents of the organization.
Okay, yeah.
Set it up where they could be elected.
But we had some slots in there where
The treasurer had to be on the foundation.
The president had to be on the foundation.
And then we went out and picked, I think we had a seven-member board.
I think we had five veterinarians and two public.
So we went and got a banker, got a livestock man on there.
I believe it was a seven-member board.
The reason for it, we wanted to expand and bring in the other areas that are around us.
